dth="960" height="672" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-04.png 960w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-04-300x210.png 300w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-04-768x538.png 768w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-04-640x448.png 640w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px" /> <img class="size-full wp-image-153057 aligncenter" src="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-02.png" alt="" width="940" height="664" srcset="https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-02.png 940w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-02-300x212.png 300w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-02-768x543.png 768w, https://businesstech.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Harbour-Arch-02-640x452.png 640w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px" /> While rezoning for the new project was approved as far back as 2012, the development has faced a number of hurdles – including objections from affordable housing activists. They argued that there was a lack of affordable housing included in the development, which they believed would further exclude poor and working-class people from the city centre. They called on the City to reject the application until it included the provision of affordable housing either within the development itself or the surrounding area. Read: Cape Town approves R14 billion Foreshore development – despite objections 